1. Phishing
Definition

Phishing is a fraudulent technique where attackers pretend to be trusted organizations to steal usernames, passwords, banking information, or other confidential data.

Example

A user receives an email claiming to be from PayPal requesting immediate account verification through a fake website.

Prevention
Verify website URLs carefully.
Never click suspicious links.
Enable MFA.
Report suspicious emails.
2. Malware
Definition

Malware is harmful software created to damage systems, steal information, or interrupt normal computer operations.

Example

A computer becomes infected after downloading software from an untrusted website.

Prevention
Install trusted antivirus software.
Keep applications updated.
Download software only from official websites.
3. Ransomware
Definition

Ransomware locks or encrypts files and demands payment to restore access.

Example

The Colonial Pipeline ransomware attack disrupted fuel distribution across parts of the United States.

Prevention
Create regular backups.
Update operating systems.
Avoid opening unknown email attachments.
4. Social Engineering
Definition

Social engineering involves manipulating people into revealing confidential information or performing actions that compromise security.

Example

An attacker pretends to be an IT technician and asks an employee for login credentials.

Prevention
Verify identities before sharing information.
Attend security awareness training.
Never share passwords over phone or email.
5. Data Breach
Definition

A data breach occurs when confidential information is accessed or disclosed without authorization.

Example

The Equifax breach exposed personal information belonging to millions of customers.

Prevention
Encrypt sensitive information.
Restrict user access.
Regularly monitor systems for suspicious activity.
